## 5. Workflow integration: gsd × superpowers × gstack

Three vendored skill packs are installed side-by-side. They are complementary, not alternatives — each owns a distinct layer of the workflow. Apply them together rather than picking one.

| Pack | Owns | Command prefix |
|---|---|---|
| **gsd** (get-shit-done) | Phase-based spec→plan→execute lifecycle, roadmap/milestone management, multi-phase orchestration | `/gsd-*` |
| **superpowers** | Core engineering methodology: TDD, subagent-driven development, plan-writing, code-review hygiene | `/brainstorm`, `/write-plan`, `/execute-plan`, plus auto-triggering skills (`brainstorming`, `test-driven-development`, `executing-plans`, etc.) |
| **gstack** | Cognitive-mode specialists: founder taste, paranoid review, browser-based QA, design exploration, release mechanics | `/gstack-*` (47 skills: `/gstack-plan-ceo-review`, `/gstack-plan-eng-review`, `/gstack-review`, `/gstack-ship`, `/gstack-qa`, `/gstack-browse`, `/gstack-design-shotgun`, `/gstack-investigate`, `/gstack-retro`, etc.) |

### Composition rule (MANDATORY)

**gstack's gears run inside gsd's phases, not instead of them.** Never substitute a gstack command for its gsd equivalent — they have different contracts. gsd commands write to `.planning/` and advance phase state; gstack commands are stateless cognitive passes. Run gstack as a rigor layer *within* the gsd phase that needs it.

### Canonical phase-to-gear mapping

| gsd phase | Superpowers skill | gstack gear to run inside it | Why |
|---|---|---|---|
| `/gsd-spec-phase` (defining WHAT) | `brainstorming` auto-triggers | `/gstack-plan-ceo-review` | Founder-mode pressure-tests whether the spec is describing the *right* product before it's locked |
| `/gsd-discuss-phase` (gathering context) | — | `/gstack-plan-eng-review` | Tech-lead mode surfaces architecture constraints, failure modes, and diagrams before planning |
| `/gsd-plan-phase` (writing PLAN.md) | `writing-plans`, `test-driven-development` | — | gsd-planner + superpowers TDD is sufficient here; don't layer a third planner |
| `/gsd-execute-phase` (implementing) | `executing-plans`, `subagent-driven-development`, `dispatching-parallel-agents` | — | Superpowers owns execution; gstack doesn't overlap |
| `/gsd-code-review` (pre-ship audit) | `requesting-code-review`, `receiving-code-review` | `/gstack-review` | Paranoid-staff-engineer mode hunts production-killing bugs (N+1, race conditions, trust-boundary violations) that gsd's reviewer may miss |
| `/gsd-verify-work` (UAT) | — | `/gstack-qa` or `/gstack-qa-only` | Browser-based diff-aware verification — reads the diff, spins up Chromium, tests every affected page |
| `/gsd-ship` (PR creation) | `finishing-a-development-branch` | `/gstack-ship` (optional) | gsd-ship handles planning-aware PRs; use gstack-ship only when operating outside a gsd phase |
| After milestone completion | — | `/gstack-retro` | Data-driven retrospective from commit history; feeds back into the next `/gsd-new-milestone` |

### When NOT to use a pack

- **Don't use gstack-ship inside a gsd phase** — it bypasses `.planning/` state. Use `/gsd-ship` instead.
- **Don't use gstack-plan-ceo-review after code is already written** — its value is pre-spec; after implementation it becomes scope-creep theater.
- **Don't use gsd alone for pure exploratory coding** — spec→plan→execute overhead isn't worth it for a one-file script. Use superpowers' `/brainstorm` and TDD directly.
- **Don't run gstack-review AND gsd-code-review on the same diff and merge findings** — run gstack-review first (broader paranoid pass), then gsd-code-review (phase-aware, writes REVIEW.md). Sequential, not redundant.

### Per-milestone demo-validate escalation (Salesforce demo work)

When a milestone produces or depends on a demo-ready Salesforce org, run `sf-demo-validate` against the milestone spec **after** `/gsd-verify-work` passes. `sf-demo-validate` carries its own 200-pt rubric and autonomous self-repair for in-scope issues (missing metadata, demo-data drift, broken demo automation). If validation fails:

| Failure type | Escalate to | Why |
|---|---|---|
| In-scope, self-repairable (metadata/data/automation gaps) | `sf-demo-validate` repairs and re-runs itself | Stay inside the skill — it owns this scope |
| Self-repair blocked, still in-phase (touches phase artifacts, may span sessions) | `/gsd-debug` | Persistent state, integrates with `.planning/`, scientific method |
| Out-of-scope (org-config oddity, infra, anything outside the phase) | `/gstack-investigate` | Stateless 4-phase root-cause loop, no phase overhead |

**Default tiebreaker:** if you're mid-milestone in GSD, prefer `/gsd-debug` — it preserves context for the rest of the milestone. Reach for `/gstack-investigate` only when the issue is clearly outside phase scope.

**Never skip the escalation.** A `sf-demo-validate` failure that isn't repaired is a milestone regression — do not advance to `/gsd-ship` with a red validate verdict.

`sf-demo-validate` is **not** a generic per-milestone smoke test. For non-demo work, the right gates are `/gsd-verify-work` (UAT) plus `/gstack-qa` for UI-bearing changes — sf-demo-validate fires only when the work is demo readiness.

### Demo-pipeline orchestration (org connect → presenter-ready)

When the user's intent is "build me a demo from these notes" / "prep a demo" / "take me from discovery to presenter-ready", the canonical path is `sf-demo-orchestrate`, **not** an ad-hoc chain of demo-* skills. The orchestrator runs the 7-step pipeline (org connect + baseline → notes intake → product detection + cross-cloud routing → product + duration approval gate → demoscript → data seeding → validate/repair loop → Playwright pre-flight + presenter guide) and emits a single `DEMO-PIPELINE-STATUS.md` that tracks every score, decision, and artifact.

**Standard entry sequence:**

1. User connects an org (or `sf-demo-orchestrate` Phase 1 captures it).
2. User dumps discovery notes / requirements.
3. `sf-demo-orchestrate` fires automatically on demo-prep trigger phrases — Phase 3 prompts for **demo duration** (Short 15 min / Standard 30 / Deep 45-60) before authoring; the duration bounds story depth, step count, and visual count.
4. If the discovery notes mention **Experience Cloud / portal / public-facing UI** (or any visual surface where the user benefits from seeing options before commit), proactively co-suggest `/gstack-design-shotgun` *between* product approval (Phase 3) and demoscript authoring (Phase 4). It generates multiple design variants and opens a local comparison board so the user picks a direction before sf-nonprofit-experience-cloud-build / sf-experience-cloud locks in the implementation.
5. The validate/repair loop in Phase 6 follows the **demo-validate escalation chain** documented above — `/gsd-debug` (in-phase) or `/gstack-investigate` (out-of-scope) when self-repair is blocked.

**Note on `brainstorming` vs `gstack-design-shotgun`:** brainstorming is dialogue-only (clarifying questions → design doc). It does NOT generate localhost UI previews. Design-shotgun is the variant generator with the comparison board — that's the one to reach for when "show me what this could look like" is the ask.

**Don't bypass the orchestrator** by chaining demo-* skills manually for a full pipeline run. Manual chaining loses the status file, skips the duration gate, and risks running phases out of order. Use individual demo-* skills only for partial work (just author, just seed, just validate) — `sf-demo-orchestrate`'s `DO NOT TRIGGER when:` clause already routes those correctly.

### Browser-based QA note

`/gstack-qa`, `/gstack-qa-only`, `/gstack-browse`, and `/gstack-setup-browser-cookies` require a Bun-compiled Chromium binary at `NGOSkills/.vendor/gstack/browse/dist/browse`. The `scripts/vendor-hooks/gstack-post-install.sh` hook rebuilds it on every pin bump. If a `/gstack-qa` invocation fails with "browse binary missing", run:

```bash
~/Cursor/Skills/NGOSkills/scripts/vendor-install.sh gstack
```

### Supply-chain review: updates flow through one pipeline

All three packs update via the same mechanism:

1. `scripts/auto-update-skills.sh` (hooked to Claude Code SessionStart) pulls NGOSkills updates
2. A landed commit bumps `vendor-pins.txt` (SHA changes are one-line diffs, reviewed in PR)
3. `scripts/vendor-install.sh` materializes the new SHA in `.vendor/<slug>/`
4. Per-vendor post-install hooks (in `scripts/vendor-hooks/`) run if present — e.g., gstack rebuilds its Chromium binary and relinks its skills
5. `scripts/sync-skills.sh --fix` fans out symlinks into `~/.claude/` and `~/.cursor/`

Never install a vendor pack out-of-band (directly cloning into `~/.claude/skills/`, running a vendor's own `setup` from a random location, etc.). That breaks the supply-chain review trail and creates drift the audit scripts can't catch.

